(ii)  quality and relevance: 

(a)  pass percentage in examinations improved by 25%; 
(b)  qualifications,  experience,  and  skills  of  25–50%  of  TEVT  teachers 
improved; 
(c)  education standard and evaluation system improved,  
(d)  facilities and instructional materials upgraded, and 
(e)  new technologies and trades introduced to meet emerging market needs; 

(iii)  institutional efficiency: 

(a)  dropout rates reduced by 25%; 
(b)  TEVT institutions have greater autonomy and improved management; 
(c)  R&D cell integrated with DTE and strengthened, with LMIS and MIS to 
improve information and analyses on key TEVT issues; and 
(d)  more than 25% of TEVT institutions are able to establish linkages with the 
industry. 

6.  All this progress will be made during the project period (2005–2010) and progress 
achieved over the baseline to be established during the first year of the Project. 

7.  MIS will focus on the following information: 

(i)  students:  number  of  applications,  admission,  enrollment,  dropout  rates, 
examination performance, and employment rates by program and gender; 

(ii)  teachers’ expertise, experience, qualification, and training; 
(iii)  expertise,  experience,  qualification,  and  training  of  management  and 
administration staff; 
(iv)  financing: capital cost and recurrent cost by standard budget items, and unit cost; 

(v)  facilities: number of classrooms, workshops, other areas, equipment, furniture 
and their condition; 

8.  The LMIS will focus on the following information and complement the MIS to avoid 
duplication: 

(i)  demand  and  supply  of  labor  (local  market,  international  market,  self-
employment);  
(ii)  skills required (based on labor market survey; interaction with industry, private 
sector, Overseas Pakistan Association); 
(iii)  labor market trend and labor force statistics by key sectors; 
(iv)  information on job openings and types of jobs; 
(v)  information on apprenticeship, internship, and voluntary work; and 
(vi)  job opportunities.
